g.text: Socrates
Truth is comprehended only in live discussions.
is about searching the truth and reaching the true knowledge with a series of
discussions and questions being asked on that discussion, which aids in clarifying the
definition and discussion. Thus, it is about reaching truth with short, direct
answers to questions. It is filled with irony. For example, you ask a person what is
"good" then listen to him, agree with him and then ask more specific questions from
general description he gave you. Then it finds out what that person is not really
knowing the subject. This method should cheer a person to dig deeper and start
thinking.
1. Questioning: The Socratic method begins with a question. But it’s not just any
question — it’s often a simple, yet profound inquiry into the nature or definition of a
concept, such as “What is justice?”
2. Elenchus (Refutation): As the dialogue progresses, Socrates would often point out
contradictions in the other person’s answers, pushing them to refine or rethink their
position.
3. Acknowledging Ignorance: One of the hallmark moments in many Socratic dialogues is
the recognition of one’s own ignorance. Socrates himself often claimed that his wisdom
was limited to knowing that he knew nothing.
4. Pursuit of Truth: The dialogues are not mere debates. Rather, they are co-
operative endeavours between the participants to uncover the truth.
5. Iterative Nature: The Socratic dialectic isn’t linear. It is iterative, often moving
back and forth as positions are revised and refined in light of new insights.
